@bowlofgumbo  
Yes, those cards ([Ancestral Recall](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Ancestral Recall) and [Time Walk](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Time Walk)) are inherently broken, but a deck full of just [Ancestral Recall](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Ancestral Recall) and [Time Walk](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Time Walk) is not going to win you the game. It's the other cards in the relevant format that make a card broken.  

What makes [Geist of Saint Traft](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Geist of Saint Traft) broken is that the other cards available in the pool of today's standard aren't good enough to deal with him without some inherent loss. Cards that do deal with him are too narrow or too costly. You can't block him if your opponent plays [Restoration Angel](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Restoration Angel) or [Spectral Flight](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Spectral Flight) in their deck. [Rolling Temblor](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Rolling Temblor) is too narrow for the main board, as it does not hit flyers and is sorcery speed. [Supreme Verdict](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Supreme Verdict) comes out a turn too late, and again, sorcery. [Barter in Blood](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Barter in Blood) and [Mutilate](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Mutilate) will sometim... [(see all)](javascript:void(0);)
